 uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Ednywain Ap Eginir was born about 1100, in Montgomery, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom. She married Ednywain Ap Eginir about 1130, in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1100–":"umbes 1100–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1132–1215":"1132–1215","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","Abt 1130":"umbes 1130","1090":"1090","1215":"1215","1100":"1100","1132":"1132","1175":"1175","1152":"1152","about 1132":"umbes 1132","about 1100":"umbes 1100","about 1175":"umbes 1175","Montgomery, Powys, Wales":"Montgomery, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom",",Merionethshire,Wales.":"Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Of Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Tegeingl ctf, Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1100–":"noin 1100–Kuollut","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1132–1215":"1132–1215","1152–Female":"1152–Kuollut","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","Abt 1130":"noin 1130","1090":"1090","1215":"1215","1100":"1100","1132":"1132","1175":"1175","1152":"1152","about 1132":"noin 1132","about 1100":"noin 1100","about 1175":"noin 1175","Montgomery, Powys, Wale